node.text:
Japanese club kid, drag queen, DJ, and more, Kifujin (@kifujin_yx) has been a popular personality in the Tokyo street fashion scene for years. We've snapped Kifujin countless times on the streets of Harajuku, and his style is always his own. Please check out this short English-subtitled video interview he was kind enough to sit for on the street in Harajuku! Kifujin has been studying English so you can leave a comment for him in English or follow his personal Instagram. Special thanks to @rikarin0526 for asking the questions.

Also let us know in the comments which other Harajuku kids you'd like to see interviews with in the future!

node.text:
Sakuran (@sakuran_is_) is an 18-year-old Japanese fashion student known in the Tokyo street fashion scene for her one-of-a-kind remake outfits. She grew up in a small town 1,000 km from Tokyo, but discovered her love of extreme fashion on a trip to Harajuku when she was in 8th grade.

We meet thousands of people a year while shooting Tokyo street fashion, but Sakuran stood out from the first time we met her. Her style and confidence have continued evolving, and we are excited to see where life will take her. Please check out this short interview and her personal Instagram account too.

#Harajuku #JapaneseFashion #JapaneseStreetFashion #streetfashion #fashion #style #Tokyo #Japan #原宿 #ファッション #TokyoFashion #art #JapaneseDesigner #FashionStudent #extremefashion #avantgardefashion

node.text:
Interview with Shouta (@tananasho), a 26-year-old Japanese musician (drums & guitar), model, and aspiring actor who has long been active in the Harajuku street fashion scene. Shouta talks about his dreams of music, how he got into fashion, how he's working to turn self doubt into something positive, and much more. She posts a lot of modeling photos on his own Instagram if you'd like to see more. 
#Harajuku #JapaneseFashion #JapaneseStreetFashion #streetfashion #fashion #style #Tokyo #Japan #原宿 #ファッション #TokyoFashion

node.text:
Interview with 18-year-old Japanese art student Sakurako (@illbabigstar). She first came to Harajuku in 7th grade and has been making friends in the neighborhood ever since. In the interview she talks about what Harajuku means to her, the disappearance of print fashion magazines, her favorite teacher, why she chose art over fashion as a career, and lots of other stuff. To see her art, follow Sakurako on Instagram.
#Harajuku #JapaneseFashion #JapaneseStreetFashion #streetfashion #fashion #style #Tokyo #Japan #原宿 #ファッション #TokyoFashion #art #JapaneseArt #JapaneseArtist
